<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1778,1949]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1778,1803]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName=": d'Abrera" authorityYear="1971" box="[284,565,1779,1803]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Libythea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="geoffroyi" subSpecies="genia">
<emphasis box="[284,565,1779,1803]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Libythea geoffroyi genia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<emphasis box="[792,952,1779,1803]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
L. g. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1901" box="[857,952,1779,1803]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Libythea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alompra">alompra</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
because both have similar dorsal surface coloration, but it can be distinguished by the presence of a bright white discal cell mark and a white mark between M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[176,184,1866,1880]" fontSize="6" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">3</subScript>
and CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[291,299,1866,1880]" fontSize="6" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">2</subScript>
. The hindwing dorsum of both sexes has a narrow orange band from M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1102,1110,1866,1880]" fontSize="6" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">1</subScript>
to CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1199,1207,1866,1880]" fontSize="6" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">1</subScript>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
